In .NET MAUI, `Application` still supports `OnStart()`, `OnSleep()`, and `OnResume()` — they work the same way. However, MAUI also introduces more granular **Window lifecycle events**, which is the recommended approach:

**Option 1 — Override `CreateWindow` and use `Window` events:**
```csharp
protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
{
    var window = new Window(new AppShell());

    window.Created  += (s, e) => { /* replaces OnStart */ };
    window.Stopped  += (s, e) => { /* replaces OnSleep */ };
    window.Resumed  += (s, e) => { /* replaces OnResume */ };
    window.Destroying += (s, e) => { /* app shutting down */ };

    return window;
}
```

**Option 2 — Platform-specific hooks in `MauiProgram.cs`:**
```csharp
builder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>
{
#if ANDROID
    events.AddAndroid(android => android
        .OnStop(activity => { /* sleep */ })
        .OnRestart(activity => { /* resume */ }));
#elif IOS
    events.AddiOS(ios => ios
        .DidEnterBackground(app => { /* sleep */ })
        .WillEnterForeground(app => { /* resume */ }));
#endif
});
```

**Key differences:**
| Xamarin.Forms | MAUI Window Event | Scope |
|---|---|---|
| `OnStart()` | `Created` | Per-window (supports multi-window) |
| `OnSleep()` | `Stopped` / `Deactivated` | Per-window |
| `OnResume()` | `Resumed` / `Activated` | Per-window |

The Window-based approach is preferred because MAUI supports **multi-window apps** (especially on iPad/desktop), so per-window lifecycle is more precise.
